Question:- HAS-A can be better than IS-A

Answer:- 
âœ… HAS-A vs IS-A
      IS-A â†’ Inheritance (e.g., class Dog extends Animal)      
      HAS-A â†’ Composition (e.g., class Car { Engine engine; })

ğŸ§  In your duck code:
      class Duck {
          FlyBehavior flyBehavior;
          QuackBehavior quackBehavior;
      }
ğŸ‘‰ This is a HAS-A relationship:

A Duck has-a FlyBehavior, A Duck has-a QuackBehavior

You're not inheriting flying or quackingâ€”you're composing the duck with those behaviors.

ğŸ’¡ Why HAS-A is better here: You can change the behavior at runtime

You donâ€™t need to modify the Duck class to add new fly types. Promotes flexibility and reuse

âœ… So the answer: The Duck class uses HAS-A relationships with FlyBehavior and QuackBehavior by holding references to those interfaces.

